{"hits": {"hits": [{"created": "2026-01-07T23:33:20.887512+00:00", "modified": "2026-01-07T23:33:21.413945+00:00", "id": 18177667, "conceptrecid": "18177666", "doi": "10.5281/zenodo.18177667", "conceptdoi": "10.5281/zenodo.18177666", "doi_url": "https://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.18177667", "metadata": {"title": "Wildlife Ethics and Practice: Why We Need to Change the Way We Talk About 'Invasive Species'", "doi": "10.5281/zenodo.18177667", "publication_date": "2020", "description": "(Uploaded by Plazi for the IPBES Invasive Alien Species Assessment) Abstract\n            This article calls for an end to the use of the term 'invasive species', both in the scientific and public discourse on wildlife conservation. There are two broad reasons for this: the first problem with the invasive species narrative is that this demonisation of 'invasives' is morally wrong, particularly because it usually results in the unjust killing of the animals in question. Following on from this, the second problem is that the narrative is also incoherent, both from scientific and philosophical perspectives. At the heart of both of these issues is the problem that the invasive species narrative oversimplifies what are in fact very complex biological processes. As a result, the policies carried out with the stated aim of 'controlling' these animals are often unethical. In light of the current global species decline, this article asserts that the way we think and talk about these animals should be changed and the term 'invasive species' should be discontinued, in the hope that this leads to changes in practice.", "access_right": "restricted", "creators": [{"name": "Inglis, Meera Iona", "affiliation": null}], "keywords": ["Chapter 1", "biodiversity", "environment assessment", "IPBES", "Alien Invasive Species Assessment AIS", "invasive species"], "related_identifiers": [{"identifier": "hash://md5/3be2fb966ac266a2985f452d0456b2e8", "relation": "hasVersion", "scheme": "url"}, {"identifier": "hash://sh